# Compliance — do not modify casually

Wording on the donate page and receipt email is legally significant. Changes need treasurer (Eran) review before merging.

## New York solicitation surfaces

NY Executive Law §174-b applies to `/donate`, donation widgets, fundraising emails, and other solicitations. Each solicitation must carry:

- A clear description of the programs and activities for which funds are sought, or directions for obtaining it.
- `<CharitiesDisclosure />`, which is the single source for the organization/Attorney General addresses, Charities Registry URL, Attorney General disclosure phone number, and report-availability language.
- While no CHAR500 is on file, the date the first report will be filed. Replace that sentence only after the first report is accepted.
- Conspicuous presentation. The web component uses fixed 14px bold text; do not add a caller override that can reduce it.

The site also states its determined §501(c)(3) status and tax deductibility on `/donate` as a donor-clarity policy. There must be no fiscal-sponsor or “determination pending” wording.

## IRS substantiation rules

- A donor claiming any single gift ≥ $250 needs a contemporaneous written acknowledgment with the organization name, amount (or noncash description), and the applicable goods-or-services statement. Our receipt also records the date and sends for every gift.
- The EIN is not an IRS-required acknowledgment field, but we include it in the receipt for donor convenience. Store it only as server-side `ORG_EIN`; never restore a `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` EIN variable or render it elsewhere on the public site.
- Quid-pro-quo gifts > $75 (e.g., gala tickets with a meal) require a fair-market-value statement.
- Year-end consolidated receipts go out by January 31 as an organization policy.

## What goes in `<ComplianceFooter />`

A single reusable component used in the marketing layout. It carries the lean set only:

- Filed legal name "MOTIVE 4 ARTISTS INC." to distinguish the nonprofit from MOtiVE Brooklyn LLC.
- Accessibility/privacy/terms links.
- Contact, social, and newsletter.

Do not add the EIN, tax-status claim, NTEE code, foundation classification, Charities registration number, or §174-b wording to the global footer. The peer benchmark found none of the sampled arts nonprofits displayed an EIN there, and no federal or New York rule requires it.

## Public records and future financials

There is no `/transparency` route. Federal law requires the 1023-EZ, determination letter, and applicable 990/990-EZ filings to be available for inspection/copying on request; posting them on a dedicated page is optional.

Create `/financials` only after an actual CHAR500, 990/990-EZ, or board-adopted annual report exists. Publish exact filed documents and verified impact results. Do not create placeholder “transparency” commitments, publish board minutes, or surface raw registry identifiers merely to fill a page.
